From ba8a7dd05a23178826ed4db48171630044e26bae Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 16:15:54 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Modules: run module init on a pumped loop and bind imports
 without Clr

Fixes the module-orchestration completion defect that left an engine-driven
static import resolving to undefined even after the top-level-await codegen fix.
Three coupled changes:

1. Pump the whole init. RunScriptAsync/RunAsync now run their core under one
   AsyncPump.Run loop on a worker thread (like JSContext.ExecuteAsync). A module
   body compiled with top-level await suspends its async continuation onto the
   ambient SynchronizationContext; on the default un-pumped context those
   continuations never drain, so the body stalled at its first await (which every
   static import desugars to).

2. Remove the compile double-marshal. JSModule gains a direct CompileDirect hook
   that InitAsync awaits instead of invoking the Compile JS function, which
   marshalled the compile Task into a JS promise and re-awaited it
   (Task -> IJSPromise -> Task). That round-trip re-posted the body's continuation
   off the running loop.

3. Bind imports without Clr. import()/require() converted their module
   Task<JSValue> to a promise via JSEngine.ClrInterop.Marshal, which is only the
   full DefaultClrInterop when the optional Broiler.JavaScript.Clr assembly is
   loaded; otherwise the fallback returns undefined for a Task. Modules does not
   reference Clr, so an imported binding silently resolved to undefined. Route
   these through the engine-native JSValue.CreatePromiseFromTask (populated by the
   always-referenced BuiltIns), so import value binding works with or without Clr.

Adds EngineModuleImportBindingTests covering named/namespace/default imports,
transitive chains, a diamond with a shared dependency evaluated once, and a
top-level-await dependency. Full Broiler.JS suite stays green (only the
pre-existing Intl/ICU-locale and doc-file env failures). Stacks on patch 0010.
